% OK groups vs individuals: hook 1
There is no agreement on when, how and why parties target individuals or groups. The distributive politics and vote-buying literatures have traditionally followed two different practices. Unfortunately, this decision seems to be grounded on the research design rather than on theoretical reasons. Consequently, it has been implied that the two strategies are interchangeable. On the one hand, the distributive politics literature has mostly focused on groups, usually districts or provinces (\citet[]{Dixit1996}, \citet[]{Khemani2015}, \citet[]{Calvo2004}). In this literature, incumbent parties deliver public-sector jobs or construction projects contingent on the support of \emph{groups} of individuals. On the other hand, the vote-buying literature has typically focused on \emph{individuals} and their characteristics such as socio-economic or electoral profiles (\citet[]{Carlin2015}). 

% OK income: hook 2
The most consolidated agreement is on the positive effects of poverty on vote-buying (\citet[]{Calvo2004,Weitz-shapiro})\footnote{Vote-buying is ``the proffering to voters of cash or (more commonly) minor consumption goods by political parties, in office or in opposition, in exchange for the recipient's vote'' (\citet[p. 67]{Brusco2004}). In the rest of this note, we use clientelism and vote-buying interchangeable.}. \citet{Kitschelt2000}\footnote{See also Kitschelt and Altamirano in \citet[ch. 10]{Carlin:2015}.}, For example, \citet{Brusco2004}, \citet[]{Stokes:2013cj} and \citet[]{Nazareno2008a} explain that since the poor derive more utility from immediate transfers than future and risky returns associated with policy packages, clientelistic political parties \emph{only} target the poor. \citet[p. 12]{Weitz-Shapiro:2014aa} explains that ``[a]lmost universally, scholars of clientelism treat and analyze the practice as an exchange between politicians and their poor clients''. However, this canonical predictor has been recently challenged. \citet{Szwarcberg2013} ``challenges the assumption [that brokers] with access to material benefits will always distribute goods to low-income voters in exchange for electoral support'', while \citet{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012} and \citet[]{Holland2015} explain that income (measured at the individual level) has little or no effect on vote-buying. Why does contemporary scholarly work report null fundings on poverty, the \emph{most} important predictor of vote-buying? Under what \emph{conditions} do poor \emph{and} non-poor individuals receive clientelism? The dataset analyzed in this paper strongly suggests that brokers do target non-poor individuals as well (see \autoref{fig:wealth:client:plot}). Why would brokers have incentives to target non-poor individuals? Currently, the literature does not offer a satisfactory answer for these questions. We present a theory that sheds light on these questions by explaining when and why group and individual targeting are efficient.


