\section*{Case Selection, Data and Design}

% explain the identification strategy, introducing Brazil as the case
The unit of analysis is individuals. Particularly, we are interested in testing the effects of individuals with different income levels, being nested in communities with different poverty sizes and being exposed to different levels of political competition, on receiving clientelism. We find Brazil to be a good case because its poverty structure allows having low-income individuals being nested in non-poor areas (and vice versa). Simply put, low income levels do not properly classify individuals into high-poverty density contexts (and vice versa). To test our hypothesis, we use survey data from 2010 from \citet{LAPOP2010}\footnote{``I thank the Latin American Public Opinion Project (LAPOP) and its major supporters (the United States Agency for International Development, the United Nations Development Program, the Inter-American Development Bank, and Vanderbilt University) for making the data available''. The sample consists of five strata representing the five main geographical regions of Brazil. Each stratum was further sub-stratified by urban and rural areas.}. To ensure that there is not a systematic relationship between personal income and the density of the poor where individuals reside, the data was preprocessed using matching techniques. In other words, based on observables, matching methods force the systematic relationship between these two variables to be zero (\citet{King2011})\footnote{\autoref{fig:municipality:wealth:large:plot} in the Appendix shows that the raw dataset have already embedded into them low levels of correlation (\Sexpr{round(cor(dat$wagehalf, dat$wealth), 2)}), while the matched dataset have even lower levels (\Sexpr{round(cor(m.data$wagehalf, m.data$wealth), 2)}).}. 


% clientelism gap / but still works
Some scholars question the effectiveness of vote-buying, pointing out to a possible decay of this practice. The main problem is that the information brokers have is more often of very low quality. As \citet[p. 15]{Carlin2015} point out, individual's ``electoral profiles are composed of behaviors that are difficult to monitor with certainty and attitudes''. For example, in Colombia, the ``electoral environment is such that brokers have a hard time identifying the preferred candidates'' (\citet[p. 5]{Rueda2016}). Given these informational constraints, \citet[p. 1139]{Dixit1996} argue that some portion of the investment will be wasted, producing a gap between what is spent on clientelism and its returns (\citet[{\color{red}Chapter?}]{Carlin:2015}). However, Brazil is still an interesting case, as it has an electoral system that \emph{incentivizes} clientelism. Several factors such as multimember districts with open lists and the institution of the \emph{candidato nato}\footnote{``[R]ule that removed parties' control over the nominations process and let an electoral legislator to decide to run on any party ticket'' (\citet[{\color{red}Chapter?}]{Carlin:2015}).}, ``clearly made Brazil one of the most personalistic systems of democratic governance'' (\citet[{\color{red}Chapter?}]{Carlin:2015}). In fact, \citet[p. 290]{Gingerich2014b} finds that vote-buying drastically changes electoral results, concluding that ``[v]ote brokerage can still pay electoral dividends in contemporary Brazil''.


