\subsection*{Density of the Poor, Political Competition and Income} 

% explain graph
Analogous to \autoref{tab:strategy:set}, \autoref{fig:plot:four:quadrants} is divided into four panels, depicting simulated probabilities of being targeted conditional on personal income, whether individuals are nested in poor/non-poor municipalities and whether individuals are exposed to contested/not-contested municipalities. The left-right panel depicts simulations for the upper (``non-poor'', 75\%) and lower (``poor'', 25\%) quartiles of the continuous \texttt{wealth index} variable. In turn, the upper-lower panel shows simulated values for the maximum value (\Sexpr{round(max(m.data$munopp),0)}\%) and lowest value (\Sexpr{round(min(m.data$munopp),0)}\%) of the \texttt{municipal opposition} index. The X-Axis shows whether individuals are nested in poor municipalities (``high density of the poor'') or non-poor municipalities (``low density of the poor''). The plot shows two simulated probability distributions for each cell, one for the matched sample and one for the weighted sample. In the case of the weighted sample, ``low density'' represents the lower quartile of the continuous variable that measures the percentage of individuals living with less than half of the minimum wage. ``High density'' is the upper quartile of the same variable\footnote{However, the weighted model in \autoref{tab:1} uses the \emph{continuous} version of this variable. Here we dichotomize it for the purposes of the simulations and the plot.}.

% present the results: 1
\autoref{fig:plot:four:quadrants} suggests that brokers engage in \emph{individual} targeting when individuals are identifiable. That is when individuals are poor \emph{but} nested in low-dense municipalities (quadrant 4, with a probability of \Sexpr{round(mean(low.poor.lowcomp.m$x)*100,0)}\% of being targeted\footnote{Matched sample.}) and when individuals are not poor but nested in high-poor dense municipalities (quadrant 1, with a probability of \Sexpr{round(mean(high.rich.highcomp.m$x)*100,0)}\% of being targeted). \emph{Group} targeting is more efficient in quadrants 2 and 3. Particularly in the former, brokers take advantage of the spillover effects of vote-buying. In this setting, low-income individuals nested in poor municipalities provide enough economies of scale. Every unit invested in vote-buying is multiplied when both actual \emph{and} potential voters are electorally mobilized. Given the faster discount rates of low-income individuals, and the necessity of politicians to gather more electoral support, the probability of being targeted is one of the highest (\Sexpr{round(mean(high.poor.highcomp.m$x)*100,0)}\%). Non-poor individuals in the high-poor density condition (quadrant 1) also have one of the highest probabilities. This suggests that political competition incentivizes motivated brokers to engage in vote-buying regardless of personal income when political competition is high, targeting identifiable non-poor individuals in quadrant 1 \emph{and} groups (taking advantage of the spillovers of vote-buying) in quadrant 2. We claim that brokers employ segmented targeting strategies in a simultaneous way. Finally, we were expecting non-poor individuals nested in low-poor dense municipalities exposed to lower levels of political competition (quadrant 3) to still receive some vote-buying. We theorized that in contexts where there is less political competition, there are less checks and balances and hence incumbents have more room to move. Even when politicians are not in need of more electoral support, they still engage in this expensive form of vote-buying. 



% present the results: political competition
Our results find support for \citet{Weitz-shapiro}'s paper, i.e. in general, higher levels of political competition shift the probability of receiving vote-buying upwards. However, we also find that low levels of political competition are still associated with vote-buying. In particular, we find that political competition \emph{reverses the direction} in which the density of the poor is associated with vote-buying. When municipal mayors are more politically challenged, brokers target \emph{groups} of poor individuals in poor municipalities (quadrant 2) and non-poor \emph{individuals} nested in poor municipalities (quadrant 1). We claim that when political competition is high, brokers are in more need to gather higher levels of electoral support at the lower cost. Individual profiles in quadrants 1-2 provide the cheapest possible strategies relative to quadrants 3-4, respectively. Quadrant 1 makes use of individual and selective targeting of the most expensive clients: the non-poor. We argued before that individual targeting was expensive relative to group targeting. However, where the density of the poor is high, there cannot be a large number of non-poor individuals, reducing the net costs of this strategy. It is cheaper to target this limited number of individuals than targeting non-poor individuals in non-poor municipalities (quadrant 3). These individuals are less identifiable, and their higher incomes makes them more expensive to target as a group. Similarly, given that the poor value more instant transfers, clientelism is more effective when income is low. This is especially the case in situations where there is a large concentration of them. In this scenario, targeting propagates via spillovers. For brokers it is better to target poor individuals \emph{en masse} relying on spillovers than individually (as it happens in quadrant 4). 

\subsection*{Population Size and Organization Buying}

% introduction, say what the problem is, introduce the graph
So far we have introduced the idea that brokers shift targeting strategies, directing their resources to individuals or groups depending on the levels of (un)certainty each strategy presents. Though the argument focuses specifically on targeting, by \emph{explicitly} considering macro explanations, such as the role of the density of the poor on clientelism, this argument is novel. We agree with \citet{Carlin2015}, in that the vote-buying literature consistently looks at individual explanations (only)\footnote{\citet{Weitz-shapiro}, \citet{Rueda2014a} and others are notable exceptions.}. One of the secondary objectives of this paper is to explicitly incorporate those factors, particularly by systematizing the incentives parties have. This section tests against the density of the poor, one individual-level variable (political involvement) and one macro-variable (population size). These two variables are highly recurrent in the literature. 

% analyze the graph
\autoref{fig:pol.inv:pop.size:plot} shows a plot divided into two panels. Panel \emph{a} shows simulated expected values of receiving clientelism at different levels of political involvement. As the blue lines suggests, individuals who participate in civic associations have higher probabilities of being targeted. This is in line with findings in previous research (\citet{Schaffer2015}, \citet[p. 7]{Carreras2013}, \citet{Calvo2012}, \citet[p. 16]{Holland2015} and \citet[]{Rueda2014a}). However, once we decompose these effects, we see that being nested in high-dense areas contributes substantially more to the model. These differences are statistically significant. Panel \emph{b} shows the probability of being targeted given increments in the size of the population where individuals are nested. In line with the literature, we also see that this relation is negative (\citet[323]{Stokes2005}, \citet[10]{Kitschelt2007}, \citet[p. 67]{Magaloni:2008bq}, \citet{Rueda2016}, \citet[]{Bratton2008a} and \citet[p. 456]{Gingerich2013}). However, the effect of being nested in high-poor dense municipalities outperforms the effects of population size, suggesting spillover effects (even when income/wealth and political competition are held constant). What this exercise tells us is twofold. First, it is important to consider macro explanations of vote-buying, as they shape brokers' incentive structures when deciding when and who to target. All in all, structural factors such as the density of the poor and political competition, are one of the few and perhaps only observable factors brokers have to make decisions on regarding where to invest in clientelism. Second, population size does shift the costs of clientelism. Larger populations carry more coordination dilemmas, increasing the probability of defection, making clientelism an unsafe strategy for brokers (as panel \emph{b} suggests). However, as we have seen in this paper, these costs are alleviated when brokers take advantage of the spillover effects of clientelism. This strongly suggests that there are some costs that matter more than others. We have suggested this idea twice in this article: it is not clear how ``moral costs'' refrain democratic \emph{but} poor individuals from engaging in clientelism, and it is also not clear how ``coordination costs'' deter brokers, considering that large-sized groups potentially provides greater electoral support. As we have argued here, coordination costs should be alleviated by resorting to group targeting and taking advantage of the spillover effects of clientelism.


